&gt;
&gt; We&#39;re just beginning to add JUnit testing into our codebase.
&gt; We&#39;ve decided to put JUnit test classes into the same package, but sepeate
&gt; classes, all with proper names (e.g. MyClassTester)
&gt; This way the test classes are capable of accessing all package-protected
&gt; methods,
&gt; and its relatively easy to remove the test classes from production JARs
&gt; (either by
&gt; filtering them out from a JAR, or by using a tool such as ANT which can
&gt; exclude specific
&gt; files from JARring by using a wildcard on their name.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; David Gardner &lt;david_j_gardner@...&gt;
&gt; 08/06/2001 11:33
&gt; Please respond to junit
&gt;
&gt;         To:        junit@yahoogroups.com
&gt;         cc:
&gt;         Subject:        Re: [junit] Best Practice for Tests ?
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; Hi Steven,
&gt;
&gt; I am in a similar position as yourself. I have decided
&gt; to go for the seperate directory structure. The last
&gt; option about embedding the tests in the class may make
&gt; the code basedifficult to manage. You will have to
&gt; have all of the testing resources in your classpath on
&gt; production etc which does not make much sense. There
&gt; is a tool called ANT which we will be using to manage
&gt; the codebase. You can get to build all the code run
&gt; the tests and deploy to production all in one script.
&gt; I really like Together J but I have started using
&gt; netbeans. It&#39;s totally free which my boss likes alot.
&gt; The module for junit in that will create a test class
&gt; for each class that contains empty test methods.  I am
&gt; also considering a test sub directory in each package
&gt; instead. I think the avoiding deployment of the tests
&gt; to production makes sense.
&gt;
&gt; Cheers
&gt;
&gt; David
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; --- Steven Webster &lt;steven.webster@...&gt;
&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt; I&#39;ve inherited a huge codebase which I&#39;ll be taking
&gt; &gt; over development for; as soon as
&gt; &gt; possible, I want to put skeletal JUnit tests in
&gt; &gt; place for every class; as I perform
&gt; &gt; refactorings, and as I introduce new functionality,
&gt; &gt; my intention is to first flesh out
&gt; &gt; JUnit tests, before adding feature/refactoring.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; This raises several questions, most of all related
&gt; &gt; to what are the best practices
&gt; &gt; for keeping Unit Tests alongside code.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Options as I see them:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; 1.    A separate directory tree with a root note of
&gt; &gt; test, the package structure of
&gt; &gt;       which reflects that of the codebase; keep the
&gt; &gt; tests completely isolated from
&gt; &gt;       production code, the downside being that if I
&gt; &gt; refactor code around packages,
&gt; &gt;       I have to remember to move tests as well;
&gt; &gt; also, removes my ability to test
&gt; &gt;       private and protected methods..
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; 2.    A &#39;test&#39; directory in each package of the
&gt; &gt; codebase, containing TestXXXX
&gt; &gt;       classes; with a TestXXXX class for each XXXX
&gt; &gt; class in the package above.
&gt; &gt;       Again, can&#39;t test public/protected methods,
&gt; &gt; and a little extra work is
&gt; &gt;       required to remove tests from production code,
&gt; &gt; but not that much.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; 3.    Actually make each class in the production
&gt; &gt; code it&#39;s own test, ie put the
&gt; &gt;       JUnit testing code in the class itself.  This
&gt; &gt; gives me access to protected
&gt; &gt;       and private methods, AND makes it easy to
&gt; &gt; refactor and move tests around.
&gt; &gt;       Another upside is that the JUnit plugin for
&gt; &gt; Together UML will create all
&gt; &gt;       these test skeletons for me in this manner.
&gt; &gt; Downside (and I see it as a
&gt; &gt;       pretty big downside) is that my JUnit tests
&gt; &gt; are all but impossible to remove
&gt; &gt;       from my production code.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Has anyone got any thoughts on this problem ?
&gt; &gt; Anyone been in a similar
&gt; &gt; situation, and got suggestions they could offer ?
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Cheers,
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Steven
